<TITLE> Three more days to fix power outages: officials </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Nov 17 (bdnews24.com) - Top power sector officials Saturday said it would take another three to four days to normalise the country's power supply following damage from Thursday night's cyclone. "We hope to generate 2,700 megawatts (MW) by Saturday against a peak hour demand of 2,900 MW," Power Development Board acting chairman Showkat Ali told reporters at the Dhaka Electric Supply Authority. He said: "Of the power already being generated, 800 MW is being supplied just to Dhaka city." The PDB chairman said it would take longer to restore power to the southern districts, especially Barguna and Pirojpur where facilities were badly damaged in the storm. "Power plants and distribution lines were hit hard in the Barguna and Pirojpur districts," Ali said. "It'll take timea minimum of 5 daysto normalise the power supply there." He said 1,900 MW was being generated at 4pm Saturday, and added that by Saturday night power generation would reach 2,700 MW. The country's top power sector officials, including Power Grid Company of Bangladesh managing director ABM Harunur Rashid, Dhaka Electric Supply Company managing director Saleh Ahmed, Dhaka Electric Supply Authority chairman brigadier general Nazrul Hasan and Rural Electrification Board chairman Habib Ullah Majumdar attended the press briefing. bd
